esbian feminist studies, literature, media studies, and performance studies to anthropology, education, psychology, sociology, and urban planning, this impressive interdisciplinary collection covers topics such as humanistic approaches to reading, theorizing, and interpreting, as well as scientific appeals to measurement, modeling, sampling, and statistics. By bringing together these diverse voices into an unprecedented single volume, Amin Ghaziani and Matt Brim inspire us with innovative ways of thinking about methods and methodologies in queer studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aGay and lesbian studieszUnited StatesxMethodology. 0aGay and lesbian studies-United States-Methodology. 0aQueer theoryzUnited StatesxMethodology. 0aQueer theory-United States-Methodology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Methodology.2bisacsh  aAIDS.  aAgnes Martin.  aBillie Holiday.  aBuffie Johnson.  aCLAGS.  aCounternarratives.  aHIV.  aJohn Keene.  aLGBTQ studies.  aMichael Johnson.  aPulse nightclub.  aaffect.  aattachment genealogy.  ablack lesbians.  ablack queer studies.  ablock chain.  ablues and jazz women.  achocolate cities.  ademography.  adiscursive hustling.  adyke methods.  adyke subjectivity.  aeroticism.  aessay-as-performance.  aethnography.  afeminist methods.  afield formation.  agayborhoods.  agender equality.  agender identity.  agender-fluid.  ageneral education.  aghost-document.  aheteronormativity.  aheterosexism.  aheterosexuality.  ahistory of science.  aidentity categories.  aintersectionality.  alesbian history.  amethodology.  amethods and methodology.  amigration.  anonbinary.  aopen education resources (OER).  aoral history.  aparticipatory action research.  aprovocations.  aqueer South.  aqueer history.  a